content: Machine learning is a branch of AI where systems learn patterns from data instead of fixed rules. Supervised learning uses labeled examples to map inputs to known outputs. Unsupervised learning finds structure in unlabeled data, such as clusters or latent factors. Features are measurable input variables, and labels are the target values to predict. Data quality, preprocessing, and representative sampling strongly influence model performance.

Deep learning uses neural networks with many layers to learn complex representations. Earlier layers often detect simple patterns, while deeper layers capture abstract concepts. It typically requires large datasets and high compute resources such as GPUs or TPUs. Common architectures include CNNs, RNNs, and Transformers for different problem types. Deep learning drives advances in speech recognition, language modeling, and image analysis.

Overfitting occurs when a model learns noise from training data instead of general patterns. A common sign is very high training accuracy but much lower validation accuracy. It is often caused by high model complexity, limited data, or data leakage. Regularization, dropout, early stopping, and cross-validation help reduce overfitting. Adding diverse training data and simplifying the model can improve generalization.

NLP enables computers to understand, analyze, and generate human language. Core tasks include tokenization, text classification, named entity recognition, and translation. Transformer models use attention mechanisms to capture context across long text sequences. Embeddings convert text into vectors so semantic similarity can be measured mathematically. In RAG systems, retrieval supplies grounded context to reduce hallucinations in generated answers.

Computer vision focuses on extracting information from images and videos. Typical tasks include image classification, object detection, and semantic segmentation. Models such as CNNs and Vision Transformers learn spatial features from pixel data. Preprocessing often includes resizing, normalization, and augmentation for robustness. Performance depends on high-quality annotations and coverage of real-world variability.

Model evaluation measures how well a trained model performs on unseen data. For classification, common metrics are precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC. For regression, MAE, MSE, RMSE, and R-squared are widely used. A confusion matrix highlights which classes are being confused and where errors concentrate. Reliable evaluation uses validation splits or cross-validation aligned with business objectives.

Training is the phase where model parameters are updated by minimizing a loss function. Inference is the phase where a fixed model produces predictions for new inputs. Training is usually compute-intensive and batch-oriented, often done offline. Inference prioritizes low latency, high throughput, and operational reliability. Consistent preprocessing between training and inference is essential to avoid performance drift.

A neural network is composed of layers of neurons connected by weighted links. Each neuron applies a weighted sum and nonlinear activation to transform inputs. Backpropagation computes gradients, and optimizers like Adam update model weights. Depth, width, normalization, and learning rate choices affect accuracy and stability. Modern architectures use techniques like residual connections to train deeper networks effectively.
